he'll be out stumped here! Bounces back off Buttler's gloves and Shakib is just out of his ground. commentTextItems.html: up, up and away, Woakes gets right underneath a lofted drive, clears the long-off boundary, and that is the series!

commentPostTextItems.html: 10.50pm Buttler receives the series trophy, and England claim the first spoils of their winter tour. That's it for now. Thanks for all your comments, have a read of David Hopps' match report, and we'll see you again for the first Test next week.
10.42pm Adil Rashid is Man of the Match: "It was a bit tasty there. Sometimes the bad balls get the wickets but we were trying to be confident, have a positive mindset." A man of few words.

The Man of the Series is Ben Stokes. "We left it open in the second game but took it right to the end and won it comfortably in the end. These are small steps in what we want to accomplish as a team. I'm starting to pay back the team with runs, want to take it on to India and perform there as well. Me and Jos work well, quite aggressive with bat and ball, and with our field placings. The team we've had together in the last 18 months has proved a lot of people wrong, and if we keep going we'll achieve our target of being No.1 in the world."

Mashrafe Mortaza is disappointed to have lost. "There was a lot of dew at the end and our spinners couldn't turn the ball. But England were too good. We played really well, some young players stepped up, Imrul and Tamim played well and Mushfiq returned to form."

Jos Buttler: "Physically and mentally we've stood up. We wanted to set the tone and our opening partnership set up the run chase. We could have won by seven or eight wickets. Sam Billings played fantastically well, and Ben Duckett too in his maiden series. I've been calling heads consistently and it's landed right."

10.37pm Hakim Ahmadzai: "This young England side proved to be thier best ODI side they have ever had. They played fantastic cricket in very different conditions, all credit goes to them & I am happy for thier young stand in Captain Buttler. Bangladesh also played some very good cricket over all, but they have to work a lot on thier behavior on the feild." They have certainly found some mighty fine characters. So many worthy candidates for selection. Hales and Morgan will have to justify their recalls in India.

Akhtar: "What happens to Bangladesh ICC ODI Ranking? Do they loose any points? If so how many?" It won't change much. They currently lead Pakistan by seven points, and haven't lost much ground thanks to their win in the second ODI.

10.30pm So, to England go the spoils. The highest run-chase ever pulled off in Chittagong, and paced to near-perfection, thanks to half-centuries from Sam Billings and Ben Duckett, and a cool finisher's role from Ben Stokes. Handshakes all round - that's good to see after the run-ins at Dhaka, and well earned on both sides. England know they've been in a battle in this past week.

Groucho: "Didn't Moeen say Bangladesh would suffer from the pressure if it's a tight match? Very wise, that man." He did, and he was vindicated. Though his own shot didn't do a huge amount for his argument!

Salman Ahmed Sh: "England should have won 3-0 given their form after the World Cup. But, they will take 2-1 in the absence of their Captain. It is Bangladesh's first ODI series loss in the last two and half years at the home ground." Indeed, and but for their catatonic collapse in the first ODI, it could well have been them with the 2-1 scoreline.

commentTextItems.html: good delivery, cutting back into the right hander, who pokes from deep in the crease to defend
down the leg side. Shafiul has given up the ghost now
tighter line, dead-batted to cover and Stokes jogs the single

commentPostTextItems.html: ismail lahori: "This drop catch is gonna cost series lost. England batsmen should finish is early cause last over drama is dangerous." That seems to be Stokes' plan

commentTextItems.html: it's going wrong now. An attempted variation, but it barely hits the cut strip
fuller length, pumped out to deep midwicket, and back they come for two. Single figures needed now
down the track, Stokes has had enough of this nonsense. A belligerent thwack, high into the night sky, and over long-on!
driven in the air, but too much power to be stopped by a flying short cover! Drama all over the shop, but England emerge with the upper hand

commentTextItems.html: through to the keeper once more. Two dots, at least, for Bangladesh's sake
dropped! Is that the series, there and then?! Mashrafe brought the slip into place, and Imrul got the chance that his country needed. But he muffed it! Chest height, and eminently catchable
what a strike! A big stride and spanked triumphantly through the covers! I can hear my ears pop as Chittagong draws all of the air out of the stadium
on the pads, clipped to midwicket, one more to the total ...

commentPostTextItems.html: 25 from 22 ... England still in command of their destiny

commentTextItems.html: tight line and length, met with a compact drive and a good committed tumbling dive at mid-on. One more to the total

commentPostTextItems.html: Cricfan: "It would be interesting to see which spinner gets that one over, Shakib or one of the Hossains !!" Shakib, surely. He is The Man

commentTextItems.html: outside off, and worked off a thick edge to third man. Excellent bowling. Shafiul has one more to come, and another of that tightness will make things very interesting!

commentPostTextItems.html: Nader Abbas: "Maybe luck isn't on Banglas' side...Otherwise they haven't placed a foot wrong to be on losing side." Apart from an entire beginner's foxtrot class of feet in the first ODI, of course. But I take your point!

commentTextItems.html: well bowled again, a loose drive from Woakes and he's beaten again. This is turning into a fine over. Can Shafiul close it out?
lovely bowling, an offcutter, and nibbles through the gate and just past off stump. So close!
clubbed to long-on for another single

commentPostTextItems.html: CricBellz: "The loudest in the whole stadium is the Mushfiqur behind the stumps, one can clearly listen him and the commentators sound like sitting in a quiet radio studio doing late night show :D"

commentTextItems.html: outside off and that was so close to the edge! Stokes drove on the up but wasn't quite to the pitch of the ball. The Mighty Atom grimaces behind the stumps

commentPreTextItems.html: So, England keeping pace perfectly with their run-a-ball rate. Bangladesh, not for the first time, need a wicket

commentTextItems.html: tight line and length, Stokes leans forward to defend
a leading edge on an attempted clip to leg

commentPostTextItems.html: Jimi: "So are we done with the palindromes for the day?" Get with the times. That was so first innings

dismissalText.commentary: Shakib Al Hasan st Buttler b Ali 4 (10b 0x4 0x6 13m) SR: 40

dismissalComment.html: he'll be out stumped here! Bounces back off Buttler's gloves and Shakib is just out of his ground. Was a lovely delivery, spun to beat the edge as he played forward, the bails came off and there was some confusion. Went upstairs, confirmed it wasn't bowled. Buttler didn't glove it but got lucky with the rebound and Shakib couldn't push his foot back over the line. Buttler, himself, wasn't even sure. For a moment I think he thought he'd fluffed it.

Jos Buttler b Mashrafe Mortaza 25 (26b 3x4 0x6 34m) SR: 96.15

dismissalComment.html: short, slow, and Buttler has chopped on! That was nothing more than a long-hop outside off, but it got up more than Buttler was expecting, and he has given Bangladesh a glimmer!

dismissalText.commentary: Moeen Ali c Mahmudullah b Mashrafe Mortaza 1 (3b 0x4 0x6 10m) SR: 33.33

dismissalComment.html: good grief, that is as soft as a freshly laundered duck-down pillow! Moeen has chipped a catch so tame to mid-on that it might has well have said woof and begged for a doggy-drop on the way down! It was full length, angled into the pads, and he somehow got right underneath his stroke. Mahmudullah merely had to back-pedal two paces
